863	## 4.6 The TR-808 Drum Machine
864	
865	### 4.6.1 Architecture Overview
866	
867	The Roland TR-808 (1980) generates all drum sounds through analog synthesis -- no samples. Each instrument channel is a distinct analog circuit with fixed structure but voltage-controlled parameters (pitch, decay, accent). The step sequencer triggers these circuits.
868	
869	**Key insight for emulation:** the 808's characteristic sounds arise from specific circuit behaviors -- exponential pitch envelopes, nonlinear transistor characteristics, bandpass filter resonances -- not from mere approximation. Faithful emulation requires circuit-level understanding.
870	
871	### 4.6.2 Bass Drum (BD)
872	
873	The 808 bass drum uses a bridged-T oscillator circuit that generates a sine-like tone, swept rapidly downward in pitch by an exponential envelope, fed through a VCA with a slower exponential decay.
874	
875	**Signal flow:**
876	1. Triangle/sine oscillator at start pitch (~150 Hz typical)
877	2. Pitch envelope: exponential decay from start pitch to end pitch (e.g., 150 Hz -> 50 Hz over 30-100 ms)
878	3. VCA envelope: exponential decay controlling amplitude over 200-900 ms (the "decay" knob)
879	4. Slight click/transient at onset (from the circuit's fast initial impulse)
880	
881	```typescript
882	class BassDrum808 {
883	  private phase = 0;
884	  private pitchEnv = 0;
885	  private ampEnv = 0;
886	  private pitchDecay = 0;
887	  private ampDecay = 0;
888	
889	  trigger(decay: number, tone: number, sampleRate: number): void {
890	    this.phase = 0;
891	    this.pitchEnv = 1.0;
892	    this.ampEnv = 1.0;
893	    // Faster pitch decay, slower amp decay
894	    this.pitchDecay = Math.exp(-1 / (0.04 * sampleRate));    // ~40ms
895	    this.ampDecay = Math.exp(-1 / (decay * sampleRate));      // user-controlled
896	    this.startFreq = tone;
897	  }
898	
899	  private startFreq = 150;
900	  private endFreq = 50;
901	
902	  tick(): number {
903	    const freq = this.endFreq + (this.startFreq - this.endFreq) * this.pitchEnv;
904	    this.phase = (this.phase + freq / sampleRate) % 1;
905	    const osc = Math.sin(2 * Math.PI * this.phase);
906	
907	    this.pitchEnv *= this.pitchDecay;
908	    this.ampEnv *= this.ampDecay;
909	
910	    return osc * this.ampEnv;
911	  }
912	}
913	```
914	
915	For added punch, a brief attack transient (a single-sample impulse or a very short noise burst through a highpass filter) is mixed in at trigger time.
916	
917	### 4.6.3 Snare Drum (SD)
918	
919	The 808 snare combines:
920	1. A tuned sine/triangle oscillator (~180 Hz) for the body "crack"
921	2. White noise through a bandpass filter for the "snappy" sound
922	3. A fast VCA on the tone component, a slower VCA on the noise component
923	
924	```typescript
925	class Snare808 {
926	  private toneOsc: BridgedTOscillator;   // 180 Hz sine
927	  private noise: WhiteNoise;
928	  private noiseFilter: BiquadFilter;     // BPF ~1kHz, Q~1.5
929	  private toneEnv: ADSREnvelope;         // fast decay ~100ms
930	  private noiseEnv: ADSREnvelope;        // slightly slower ~150ms
931	  private snappyAmount = 0.5;            // mix ratio
932	
933	  tick(): number {
934	    const tone = this.toneOsc.tick() * this.toneEnv.tick();
935	    const filtered = this.noiseFilter.process(this.noise.next());
936	    const snap = filtered * this.noiseEnv.tick();
937	    return tone * (1 - this.snappyAmount) + snap * this.snappyAmount;
938	  }
939	}
940	```
941	
942	The "Snappy" knob on the physical 808 controls the mix between the noise component and the tonal component.
943	
944	### 4.6.4 Hi-Hats (Open/Closed)
945	
946	The 808 hi-hat generates a "metallic" sound by mixing six square wave oscillators at specific non-harmonically-related ratios (approximately: 1, 1.342, 1.563, 1.842, 2.127, 2.537 relative), creating a dense inharmonic spectrum typical of metal.
947	
948	This mix is then fed through a bandpass/highpass filter (cutoff ~8-10 kHz) and a VCA.
949	
950	The difference between closed hat (CH) and open hat (OH) is purely the envelope length: closed hat has a very short decay (~6-50 ms), open hat has a longer decay (~200 ms-1 s).
951	
952	```typescript
953	const HAT_RATIOS = [1.000, 1.342, 1.563, 1.842, 2.127, 2.537];
954	const BASE_FREQ = 400; // Hz, the base frequency for the oscillator bank
955	
956	class HiHat808 {
957	  private phases = new Float64Array(6);
958	  private envLevel = 0;
959	  private envDecay = 0;
960	  private hpf: BiquadFilter;
961	
962	  trigger(isOpen: boolean, sampleRate: number): void {
963	    this.envLevel = 1.0;
964	    const decayTime = isOpen ? 0.5 : 0.04; // seconds
965	    this.envDecay = Math.exp(-1 / (decayTime * sampleRate));
966	    // Re-trigger: phases do NOT reset (authentic 808 behavior: open hat cuts off closed hat)
967	  }
968	
969	  tick(sampleRate: number): number {
970	    let sum = 0;
971	    for (let i = 0; i < 6; i++) {
972	      const freq = BASE_FREQ * HAT_RATIOS[i];
973	      this.phases[i] = (this.phases[i] + freq / sampleRate) % 1;
974	      sum += this.phases[i] < 0.5 ? 1 : -1; // square wave
975	    }
976	    const filtered = this.hpf.process(sum / 6);
977	    this.envLevel *= this.envDecay;
978	    return filtered * this.envLevel;
979	  }
980	}
981	```
982	
983	**Mutual exclusivity:** In the authentic 808, triggering CH while OH is sustaining cuts off the OH envelope immediately (uses the same physical circuit). This is implemented by sharing a single `envLevel` state between both hat instances.
984	
985	### 4.6.5 Clap (CP)
986	
987	The 808 clap uses white noise fed through a bandpass filter, triggered with four rapid bursts in quick succession (approximately 0, 8, 16, and 24 ms apart) to simulate the acoustic scatter of multiple hands clapping. The final burst has the longest decay.
988	
989	```typescript
990	class Clap808 {
991	  private delays = [0, 0.008, 0.016, 0.024]; // seconds
992	  private envs: ADSREnvelope[];
993	  private noise: WhiteNoise;
994	  private bpf: BiquadFilter; // ~1kHz, Q~1
995	
996	  trigger(decay: number, sampleRate: number): void {
997	    // Schedule each of the four bursts
998	    // Implement via offset sample counters
999	  }
1000	
1001	  tick(): number {
1002	    const n = this.noise.next();
1003	    const filtered = this.bpf.process(n);
1004	    // Sum contributions from all four bursts based on their timing
1005	    return filtered * this.getCurrentEnvSum();
1006	  }
1007	}
1008	```
1009	
1010	### 4.6.6 Additional Instruments
1011	
1012	**Cowbell (CB):** Two square wave oscillators at 540 Hz and 800 Hz, summed and passed through a bandpass filter with a short metallic decay. Accent adds a brief additional amplitude boost at onset.
1013	
1014	**Rimshot (RS):** A combination of a very brief (~5 ms) noise burst and a short sine tone (~100 Hz), plus high-frequency click at onset. The characteristic "stick hitting rim" sound.
1015	
1016	**Clave (CL):** A sharp, high-Q bandpass-filtered noise click at approximately 2500 Hz with an extremely fast decay (5-10 ms).
1017	
1018	**Maracas (MA):** White noise through a highpass filter (~5 kHz) with a very short envelope (~20 ms), producing the dry, papery rattle sound.
1019	
1020	**Cowbell and toms (LT, MT, HT):** Tom voices use similar architecture to the bass drum -- a pitch-enveloped sine oscillator -- with higher start frequencies and shorter decays corresponding to low (LT), mid (MT), and high (HT) tom pitches.
1021	
1022	### 4.6.7 Step Sequencer
1023	
1024	The TR-808 step sequencer runs 16 steps per pattern at a fixed tempo, with each step either active or inactive per voice. Two patterns (A and B) can be stored and chained.
1025	
1026	```typescript
1027	interface TR808Pattern {
1028	  steps: boolean[][];  // [voice][step], 16 steps per voice
1029	  accent: boolean[];   // per-step accent flag
1030	  tempo: number;       // BPM
1031	  swing: number;       // 0-1, amount of swing (delays even-numbered steps)
1032	}
1033	
1034	class StepSequencer {
1035	  private step = 0;
1036	  private samplesSinceStep = 0;
1037	
1038	  tick(pattern: TR808Pattern, sampleRate: number, drums: Map<string, DrumVoice>): void {
1039	    const stepDuration = 60 / pattern.tempo / 4; // 1/16th note in seconds
1040	    // Swing: even steps are delayed by swing amount
1041	    const swingOffset = (this.step % 2 === 1) ? pattern.swing * stepDuration * 0.5 : 0;
1042	    const currentStepDuration = stepDuration + swingOffset;
1043	    const samplesPerStep = currentStepDuration * sampleRate;
1044	
1045	    if (this.samplesSinceStep >= samplesPerStep) {
1046	      this.samplesSinceStep -= samplesPerStep;
1047	      // Trigger active drums for this step
1048	      for (const [name, drum] of drums) {
1049	        const voiceIdx = drumVoiceIndex(name);
1050	        if (pattern.steps[voiceIdx][this.step]) {
1051	          drum.trigger(pattern.accent[this.step]);
1052	        }
1053	      }
1054	      this.step = (this.step + 1) % 16;
1055	    }
1056	    this.samplesSinceStep++;
1057	  }
1058	}
1059	```
1060	
1061	### 4.6.8 Web Audio API Implementation Strategy
1062	
1063	For the TR-808 emulation in a browser:
1064	
1065	1. **AudioWorkletProcessor per voice:** Each drum sound runs in its own AudioWorkletProcessor. The worklet-main-thread communication sends trigger messages via MessagePort with a scheduled `startTime` for sample-accurate triggering.
1066	
1067	2. **Sample-accurate triggering:** Use `audioCtx.currentTime + lookahead` for scheduling, where lookahead is typically 100 ms. This prevents early-quantum triggering artifacts.
1068	
1069	3. **Accent implementation:** The accent signal boosts the amplitude by approximately +6 dB and slightly increases decay time. Pass an `accent` flag in the trigger message.
1070	
1071	4. **Swing implementation:** Compute even-step delay in the scheduler, adding the swing offset to the scheduled AudioContext time.
1072	
1073	---
1074	
1075	## 4.7 Arpeggiator Patterns
1076	
1077	### 4.7.1 Core Patterns
1078	
1079	An arpeggiator takes a set of held notes and plays them in sequence, one at a time, at a rhythmic rate. The pattern determines the order:
1080	
1081	```typescript
1082	type ArpPattern = 'up' | 'down' | 'up-down' | 'up-down-exclusive' | 'random' | 'as-played';
1083	
1084	function buildArpSequence(notes: number[], pattern: ArpPattern, octaves: number): number[] {
1085	  const sorted = [...notes].sort((a, b) => a - b);
1086	  let sequence: number[] = [];
1087	
1088	  // Expand across octaves
1089	  for (let oct = 0; oct < octaves; oct++) {
1090	    sequence.push(...sorted.map(n => n + oct * 12));
1091	  }
1092	
1093	  switch (pattern) {
1094	    case 'up': return sequence;
1095	    case 'down': return [...sequence].reverse();
1096	    case 'up-down':
1097	      return [...sequence, ...([...sequence].reverse())];
1098	    case 'up-down-exclusive':
1099	      // Don't repeat top and bottom notes
1100	      return [...sequence, ...([...sequence].slice(1, -1).reverse())];
1101	    case 'random':
1102	      return shuffleArray(sequence);
1103	    case 'as-played':
1104	      // Use insertion order from notes array (not sorted)
1105	      return [...notes, ...notes.map(n => n + 12)].slice(0, octaves * notes.length);
1106	  }
1107	}
1108	```
1109

1	/**
2	 * SynthInstrument: main-thread controller for the synth AudioWorklet.
3	 * Creates AudioWorkletNode, sends voice commands, manages parameters,
4	 * connects output to mixer channel strip.
5	 *
6	 * R-EVT-08: Real-time parameter changes via MessagePort.
7	 */
8	
9	import type { SynthVoiceCommand, SynthParameterMap } from "./synth-types";
10	import {
11	  DEFAULT_SYNTH_PARAMS,
12	  WAVEFORM_TYPES,
13	  FILTER_TYPES,
14	  LFO_SHAPES,
15	} from "./synth-types";
16	import type { MixerEngine } from "@audio/mixer/types";
17	
18	export type SynthInstrument = {
19	  /** The audio output node — connect to mixer channel strip. */
20	  readonly output: AudioNode;
21	  /** Current parameter values. */
22	  readonly params: Readonly<SynthParameterMap>;
23	  /** Send a note-on to the synth. */
24	  noteOn(note: number, velocity: number, legato?: boolean): void;
25	  /** Send a note-off to the synth. */
26	  noteOff(note: number): void;
27	  /** Release all notes. */
28	  allNotesOff(): void;
29	  /** Set a synth parameter (forwarded to worklet). */
30	  setParam<K extends keyof SynthParameterMap>(
31	    key: K,
32	    value: SynthParameterMap[K],
33	  ): void;
34	  /** Connect to a mixer channel. */
35	  connectToMixer(mixer: MixerEngine, trackId: string): void;
36	  /** Disconnect from mixer. */
37	  disconnectFromMixer(mixer: MixerEngine, trackId: string): void;
38	  /** Clean up all resources. */
39	  dispose(): void;
40	};
41	
42	/** URL for the worklet processor module */
43	const PROCESSOR_URL = new URL("./synth-processor.ts", import.meta.url);
44	
45	/**
46	 * Create a SynthInstrument connected to the given AudioContext.
47	 * Must call `audioCtx.audioWorklet.addModule()` first via loadWorkletModule().
48	 */
49	export async function createSynthInstrument(
50	  ctx: AudioContext,
51	): Promise<SynthInstrument> {
52	  // Load the worklet module
53	  await ctx.audioWorklet.addModule(PROCESSOR_URL.href);
54	
55	  const node = new AudioWorkletNode(ctx, "synth-processor", {
56	    numberOfInputs: 0,
57	    numberOfOutputs: 1,
58	    outputChannelCount: [2],
59	  });
60	
61	  const params: SynthParameterMap = { ...DEFAULT_SYNTH_PARAMS };
62	
63	  function postCommand(cmd: SynthVoiceCommand): void {
64	    node.port.postMessage(cmd);
65	  }
66	
67	  const instrument: SynthInstrument = {
68	    output: node,
69	    params,
70	
71	    noteOn(note: number, velocity: number, legato = false): void {
72	      postCommand({ type: "noteOn", note, velocity, legato });
73	    },
74	
75	    noteOff(note: number): void {
76	      postCommand({ type: "noteOff", note });
77	    },
78	
79	    allNotesOff(): void {
80	      postCommand({ type: "allNotesOff" });
81	    },
82	
83	    setParam<K extends keyof SynthParameterMap>(
84	      key: K,
85	      value: SynthParameterMap[K],
86	    ): void {
87	      (params as Record<string, unknown>)[key] = value;
88	
89	      // Map enum types to numeric index for the worklet
90	      let numericValue: number;
91	      if (typeof value === "string") {
92	        // Lookup string in appropriate type array
93	        switch (key) {
94	          case "osc1Type":
95	          case "osc2Type":
96	            numericValue = WAVEFORM_TYPES.indexOf(
97	              value as (typeof WAVEFORM_TYPES)[number],
98	            );
99	            break;
100	          case "filterType":
101	            numericValue = FILTER_TYPES.indexOf(
102	              value as (typeof FILTER_TYPES)[number],
103	            );
104	            break;
105	          case "lfo1Shape":
106	          case "lfo2Shape":
107	            numericValue = LFO_SHAPES.indexOf(
108	              value as (typeof LFO_SHAPES)[number],
109	            );
110	            break;
111	          default:
112	            numericValue = 0;
113	        }
114	      } else {
115	        numericValue = value;
116	      }
117	
118	      postCommand({
119	        type: "setParam",
120	        key: key as string,
121	        value: numericValue,
122	      });
123	    },
124	
125	    connectToMixer(mixer: MixerEngine, trackId: string): void {
126	      const strip = mixer.getOrCreateStrip(trackId);
127	      node.connect(strip.inputGain);
128	    },
129	
130	    disconnectFromMixer(_mixer: MixerEngine, _trackId: string): void {
131	      node.disconnect();
132	    },
133	
134	    dispose(): void {
135	      node.disconnect();
136	      node.port.close();
137	    },
138	  };
139	
140	  return instrument;
141	}
